    public class FindingMultipleMissingElements {
    public static void main(String args[]) {
        int i = 0;
        int a[] = { 6, 7, 8, 9, 11, 12, 13, 16, 17, 18 };
        int diff = a[0] - 0;
        for (i = 0; i &lt; a.length; i++) {
            if(a[i]-i != diff)
            {
                while(diff&lt;a[i]-i)
                {
                    System.out.println(i + diff);
                    diff++;
                }
            }
        }

    }
}


 - In this solution, you use the indices in the Natural Number array to your advantage.
 - Initialize the diff variable, which stores the difference of the first index, element 6 in this example, against 0 (first index in the array) 
 - Why do this? If you traverse an Natural Number Array and subtract the 
 element against the index of the said element, it should return the value 
 at the first index, consistently. For example:) 6-0=6 at index 0. 7-1=6 at 
 index 1. 8-2=6 at index 2. 9-3=6 at index 3. 11-4=5 at index 7. Notice this 
 difference. 
 - Now, we want to traverse through the entire array, calling the for loop.
 - We need a condition if statement to check against this difference, and nest a while loop. This while loop will check for the missing elements, with the use of the indexes. 
 - Once the counter meets the contiguous index, the while loop is terminated. 
- Time Complexity: Big O(n)

